    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Race for No. 2: A Debate With a Difference</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Penn Rhodeen letter disputes October 5 editorial calling for Democratic vice presidential candidate Sen Joseph I Lieberman to give up Connecticut race for US Senate</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mr. Lieberman's Job Program'' (editorial, Oct. 5):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Mr. Lieberman's Job Program'' (editorial, Oct. 5):</p>
        <p>In calling for Senator Joseph I. Lieberman to leave the Connecticut race for the Senate, you disregard those Connecticut Democrats who want to keep him there, seniority intact, if the vice presidency is not to be his. The suggestion that it would be better for party leaders to hand out a last-minute nomination to their personal favorite conflicts with modern democratic principles. Many of us in Connecticut want Senator Lieberman in the Senate next year -- either as a senator or as president of the Senate.</p>
        <p>Changing the law to elect a successor in a few months instead of two years if Senator Lieberman becomes vice president is a better approach. Speeding up the election advances democracy by mitigating the unfair campaign advantage that goes with the appointment of a temporary replacement by the governor. Better still would be to scrap the current replacement system, an anti-democratic relic.</p>
        <p>PENN RHODEEN  New Haven, Oct. 5, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
